  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/ontology#ITN250">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#Interaction"/>
    <rdfs:label>ITN250</rdfs:label>
    <interactsWith rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#S169"/>
    <hasInteractionDescription>Drugs like probenecid or sulfinpyrazone (used for gout) can block the way your kidneys remove Macrobid from your blood. This can cause higher levels of the drug in your body but lower levels in your urine where it is needed to fight bacteria.</hasInteractionDescription>
    <hasClinicalEffects>Higher blood levels can increase your risk of side effects like nausea, headache, or nerve problems. Lower urine levels may make Macrobid less effective, leading to persistent urinary infections.</hasClinicalEffects>
    <hasManagementAdvice>Your doctor may monitor your blood and urine closely if you take these drugs with Macrobid. They may adjust your dose or suggest using a different medication combination to avoid problems.</hasManagementAdvice>
    <hasReference rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#R161"/>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/ontology#R137">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#Reference"/>
    <rdfs:label>R137</rdfs:label>
    <hasReferenceTitle>Lower Respiratory Tract Infection</hasReferenceTitle>
    <hasAuthor>Medical News Today</hasAuthor>
    <retrievedFrom>https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/324413#symptoms</retrievedFrom>
    <publishedIn rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#integer">2025</publishedIn>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://example.org/ontology#ITN138">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#Interaction"/>
    <rdfs:label>ITN138</rdfs:label>
    <hasManagementAdvice>(No specific advice provided in source, but monitor for efficacy).</hasManagementAdvice>
    <interactsWith rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#S112"/>
    <hasClinicalEffects>Results in decreased steady-state Zidovudine concentrations.</hasClinicalEffects>
    <hasReference rdf:resource="http://example.org/ontology#R019"/>
    <hasInteractionDescription>Simultaneous oral administration with Clarithromycin.</hasInteractionDescription>
